                   sight. From Spitzer spectroscopy, we identify ice
                   absorption bands due to H2O at 5.8 mum and CO2 at 15
                   mum. The spectral energy distribution is consistent
                   with a massive, luminous (Ëœ2 Ã— 104 L &sun;) central
                   source surrounded by a dense, warm circumstellar disk
                   and envelope of total mass Ëœ500-700 M &sun;, with
                   large bipolar outflow cavities. The combination of
                   distinctive far-IR spectral features suggest that
                   IRAS 19312+1950 should be classified as an accreting,
