                   displayed by most molecules in IRC +10216, indicating
                   an origin in the inner stellar envelope. The J=3-->2
                   line is particularly narrow (DeltaV1/2~1-2 km s-1),
                   and consists of two separate velocity components at
                   VLSR~-26 and -22 km s-1. These characteristics are
                   suggestive of weak maser action in this transition.
                   The narrow line widths observed in the other
                   transitions indicate a source size <~0.5", which
                   implies a CS column density in the v=1 state of
                   ~2-6Ã—1016 cm-2. The ground-state (v=0) column
                   density is therefore on the order of 0.8-2Ã—1018 cm-2
                   for Tvib=500 K. The fractional abundance of CS
                   relative to H2 is consequently f~3-7Ã—10-5 at ~14 R*.
                   Such a high abundance close to the stellar
                   photosphere is strong evidence that CS is a
                   ``parent'' molecule in IRC +10216, as suggested by
                   infrared studies of the v=0-->1 vibrational
                   transition and interferometric observations.},
  doi =           {10.1086/317242},
}

@article{Sato2010a,
  author =        {{Sato}, M. and {Reid}, M.~J. and {Brunthaler}, A. and
                   {Menten}, K.~M.},
  journal =       {\apj},
  month =         sep,
  pages =         {1055-1065},
  title =         {{Trigonometric Parallax of W51 Main/South}},
  volume =        {720},
  year =          {2010},
  abstract =      {We report measurement of the trigonometric parallax
                   of W51 Main/South using the Very Long Baseline Array.
